  "slug": "saint-honore-gateau",
  "title": "Gâteau Saint-Honoré",
  "subtitle": "Caramelised choux puffs on a puff pastry base with Chiboust cream",
  "excerpt": "The classic Parisian patisserie: a round of puff pastry with a ring of choux paste baked on top, filled with lightened Chiboust cream, and crowned with choux puffs dipped in hard caramel and fixed in a ring.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "The Gâteau Saint-Honoré was created in the mid-nineteenth century at Chiboust's patisserie on the Rue Saint-Honoré in Paris, and named in honour of the patron saint of bakers and pastry chefs. Chiboust himself invented the cream that bears his name, a pastry cream lightened with Italian meringue. The recipe was published in Urbain Dubois and Emile Bernard's La Cuisine Classique (1856, third edition 1876), now in the public domain. The method follows this classic approach.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Saint-Honoré is a cake assembled from three separate preparations: choux paste,",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "Chiboust cream",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "term": "Chiboust cream",
                  "termId": "cmpbd0vbw00007cv4g15rr3dt"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": ", and ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "hard caramel",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "term": "hard caramel",
                  "termId": "cmpbd0vci00017cv4k44orohu"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": ", each one straightforward in isolation. Work from a mise en place: bake the base and puffs first, make the cream while they cool, and cook the caramel last because it must be used immediately. The caramel reaches 155°C; if hot caramel touches skin, run cold water over it for at least ten minutes and seek medical care if needed. Domestic ovens drift by 20°C or more; use an oven thermometer for the pastry stages.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
