        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Prepare the puff pastry base",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Preheat the oven to 200°C conventional. Roll the puff pastry to a 24 cm round and place on a lined baking tray. Prick all over with a fork to prevent the base rising unevenly. Pipe a ring of choux paste around the edge using a 1 cm plain nozzle, pressing it onto the pastry so it adheres. Pipe the remaining choux paste into 8 to 10 small puffs on a separate lined tray. Bake both trays for 25 to 30 minutes until the choux is golden and the base is cooked through. Cool on racks.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Make the Chiboust cream",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Make a vanilla pastry cream: whisk yolks, 80 g sugar, and cornflour; bring milk to simmer; temper and cook until thick. Squeeze the gelatine dry and stir into the hot pastry cream until dissolved. Keep warm. Make an Italian meringue: dissolve the 120 g sugar in 40 ml water and boil to 121°C. Whip the egg whites to soft peaks in the stand mixer, then pour the hot syrup in a thin stream with the mixer running on medium. Continue on high until glossy and cooled. Fold the warm (not hot) pastry cream into the meringue in two additions. Use the Chiboust cream immediately; it sets as it cools.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Cook the caramel and assemble",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Dissolve the 200 g sugar in 60 ml water in a pan, then cook to 155°C without stirring. Working quickly, dip the top of each small puff into the caramel and immediately press the caramelised top against the choux ring on the pastry base, spacing them evenly around the ring. Fill the centre of the Saint-Honoré with the Chiboust cream, using a Saint-Honoré piping nozzle (a flat nozzle with a 'V' cut) for the traditional striped effect, or use a star nozzle for wavy rosettes. Refrigerate for 30 minutes before serving.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
